## ğŸ§± **1. Azure Physical Infrastructure â€“ Overview**

Azureâ€™s physical infrastructure is the **foundation** of Microsoftâ€™s cloud â€” made up of **datacenters**, **regions**, and **availability zones**, which ensure **resiliency, reliability, and global reach**.

---

### ğŸŒ **2. Azure Physical Components (with Simple Examples)**

| Component                  | Description                                                                                                | Example                                                               |
| -------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Datacenter**             | Physical buildings with servers, storage, networking, power, and cooling.                                  | Like a â€œserver warehouseâ€ in Hyderabad or Singapore.                  |
| **Region**                 | A **geographical area** containing one or more datacenters connected by low-latency networks.              | Example: **Central India**, **East US**, **North Europe**.            |
| **Availability Zone (AZ)** | **Physically separate datacenters** within a region, each with independent power, cooling, and networking. | Example: **Central India Zone 1**, **Zone 2**, **Zone 3**.            |
| **Region Pair**            | Two regions **at least 300 miles apart**, backing each other up for disaster recovery.                     | Example: **East US â†” West US**, **Southeast Asia â†” East Asia**.       |
| **Sovereign Region**       | Azure regions isolated for **government or compliance** needs.                                             | Example: **US Gov Virginia**, **China North** (operated by 21Vianet). |

